Given that ICP occurs within the support layer, altering the hydrodynamic conditions, such as increasing cross-flow and flow turbulence, cannot resolve this issue [55]. In ICP, the structure of the porous support layer holds significant importance, as it greatly influences the control of ICP in an FO membrane. The structure of this porous support layer can be defined by its structure parameter (S), which serves as a benchmark for evaluating ICP in the porous layer. The S parameter indicates the mass transfer resistance inside the porous support layer, illustrating the mean diffusion distance across this layer [56,57]. The S value is calculated by multiplying the support layer thickness (ts) and tortuosity (
                           τ
                        ), and it is inversely related to porosity (
                           ε
                        ) [50]. Generally, membranes with thinner, more porous, and less tortuous supports have lower S values, enabling them to achieve reduced ICP and ultimately higher water flux [39].
